column1: When will a nominee for FBI director be confirmed by the U.S. Senate?
column5: ['Before 1 July 2017', 'Between 1 July 2017 and 31 July 2017, inclusive ', 'Not before 1 August 2017']
column6: ['US Politics']
column11: Donald Trump has yet to announce his choice to replace James Comey as the director of the FBI. The next FBI director will need to be confirmed by the U.S. Senate. The current acting replacement, Andrew G. McCabe, would also face a confirmation vote if nominated (The Hill). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help. Recommended Questions: How many removals will U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement conduct in fiscal year 2017? As of 30 November 2017, how many states, including D.C., will offer expanded Medicaid coverage to people meeting the Affordable Care Act's poverty requirements for expanded coverage? The U.S. Senate did not confirm an FBI Director before August 1st, 2017. This question closes as "c) Not before 1 August 2017." See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated.

column6: Adjusted for timeline.
Some OSINT in recent news reports related to this question:
Ahhh, healthcare.
I guess I had been right in my thinking to begin with. this isn't happening.
Time running out for full vote before Aug. 1.
This is not happening before Monday. After the failure of the healthcare bills, McConnell invoked cloture on only one nominee for a floor vote on Monday afternoon.
I got that wrong... There may be no path forward for healthcare as it failed 49-51 so on to nominations now.
Looks like it will be bumped back past Aug. 1.
It is July 27 today, making 31 july a difficult target.
Time appears to be running out for full vote on Wray before Aug. 1. Lots of factors involved that seem to get more interesting each day.

It appears the distinguished Senators are planning to spend the remaining work days of this month fulminating about health care. This will end not with a bang but a whimper (and of course a barrage of midnight Twits), and they will slog on to real business some time early August. This nomination should be high on the list then, unless their Fearful Leader instructs them that a futile foray into tax reform is more urgently required by the White House.

According to C-SPAN last night (yes, I've resorted to watching paint dry), there's about 18 hours of debate remaining on health care to be held today and tomorrow. If that's the case, and somehow the Senate wraps health care up one way or another (and keeps their recess delayed until mid-Aug), it's possible for Wray to be confirmed on 31 July.
This won't turn out well for.

Going down in forecast to August as healthcare focus/obsession by McConnell continues. Cloture was not invoked today for Christopher Wray which may indicate that it's not a priority as partisan healthcare repeal will likely be hammered throughout out the week, likely without other distractions ie. big stuff such as Trump nominee, Christopher Wray.
With healthcare actually happening I don't think this will happen before the middle of next week.
Congress has other things on its plate this week. And, it seems a few more questions are being raised about Wray.
Not looking good with the obsession to repeal healthcare.
Democratic groups: Delay FBI director vote until Trump promises to keep special counsel

Looks like Trump is trying to force Sessions and Rosenstein out, to get control over Mueller's investigation. If Mueller is eventually fired, the importance of the FBI investigation will increase. This puts the Democrats in an awkward position - they endorsed Wray earlier, but now may prefer to slow his confirmation a bit, until it's clear what is happening with Sessions/Rosenstein/Mueller. So the chances of a cloture vote increase, which would push confirmation to next week. By the way, July 31 is shown as a non-work day on the Senate's calendar.

Start off with a forecast 50/50 Variable 1: Senate focused on Healthcare +5% After 01AUG Variable 2: Historical confirmation times +5% pre 01Aug Point 1: That's an average of 20.833 days Clarence M. Kelly's 19 days from nominated to confirmed (nominated 08JUN73-confirmed 27JUN73) William H. Webster's 20 days from nominated to confirmed (nomination 20JAN78-confirmed 09FEB78) William S. Sessions 16 days from nominated to confirmed (nomination 09SEP87-confirmed 25SEP87) Louis J. Freeh 17 days from nominated to confirmed (nominated 20JUL93-confirmed 06AUG93) Robert Mueller's 15 days from nominated to confirmed (nominated 18JUL01-confirmed 02AUG01) (See "https://fas.org/sgp/crs/natsec/RS20963.pdf" for dates of nomination and confirmation.) James Comey's 38 days (nominated 21JUN13-confirmed 29July13) Variable 3: Historical time Deputy Directors hold interim Director position: +5% pre 01Aug Point 1: Historical time between new FBI directors "about 70 days on average for the five most recent Acting Directors". Point 2: McCabe started 09MAY17+70 days = approximately 16JUL17. (Quote from: https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/fbi-director-job-openings-usually-get-filled-quickly) Variable 4: Same party in control of nomination & confirmation process +2.5% pre 01Aug Point 1: President and Senate are both Republican held. Variable 5: Only need 51 members to confirm +2.5% pre 01Aug Point 1: According to precedence and law the director of the FBI confirmation requires a simple majority vote. Variable 5: Opposition party cannot filibuster confirmation vote +2.5% pre 01Aug

No movement on scheduling a vote for Wray. They can try to hold a floor vote later today after the health care debacle, or possibly tomorrow. If any Dem signals a filibuster, McConnell can invoke cloture (assuming the votes are there), which starts a 30 hour countdown. If they maintain their recess, they can push this as far as Thursday to invoke cloture with a vote on Monday, which would get us resolution on this question.

The Senate generally only sits in floor sessions a few days a week, and there are rules about how far ahead something has to be put on the calendar (although they are easily suspended). They're pretty much out of time to get this listed and voted on, especially since M. Petits-Doigts and the distinguished Senators are much distracted by the Trumpcare issue. And of course since the FBI work under the Justice Department, confirmation calculations must be adjusted now to include the imminent sacking of the Attorney General, Rod Rosenstein, and Robert Mueller.
I don't see any news reports of plans to confirm Wray this week. So it may be after Aug. 1.

Adjusting down. Whispers on the Hill are that the Senate might change its recess back to it's original start date (after this Friday, 28 July) given the almost assured failure of the health care vote. That still gives the Senate 4 days to conduct a floor vote if they invoke cloture (ending the debate - requires 51 Senators for confirmation) on Wray this afternoon. If there's not cloture after this afternoon's administrative proceedings, this becomes increasingly likely to happen in September, regardless of the recess dates as that only provides 1 additional day for this question.

Yertle the Turtle (R-Ky), the distinguished Senate Majority Leader with no majority, seems to be dragging his feet on this, presumably so he can fail once again to get a healthcare elimination bill passed. Seems an odd choice--he could pick up a cheap win for himself and President Littlefingers by calling this nomination up tomorrow and getting it passed by a large and bipartisan margin.

Because it might be a busy week for Congress, Wray's full-confirmation vote could be bumped to August. Quite a lot of new information has come out since Wray's committee hearing regarding Russia's activities.

I have been wracking, or perhaps racking, my brain to think of a reason why this wouldn't happen. Can't come up with anything, but these days just because there is no reason for something doesn't even mean it's particularly improbable. In a country run by grownups this confirmation would occur last Tuesday or so. Still, bumping up some more. Will I ever learn? Stay tuned.
It is past the first date so that's gone. He easily cleared committees with bipartisan support and McConnell indicated the intention to have him confirmed before the August recess.
With a week to go before Aug. 1, the full Senate may not vote to confirm Wray before that date. The Senate has a lot on its plate. I believe they are planning some full-Senate votes on health care.
Thanks, Dan!

Wray has been recommended to the Senate floor by a unanimous vote from the Senate Judiciary Committee (https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/07/20/senate-panel-votes-confirm-christopher-wray-new-fbi-director/495001001/).
As mentioned by @JMR2017, here's the Senate Executive Calendar (Wray on pg 10): https://www.senate.gov/legislative/LIS/executive_calendar/xcalv.pdf.

Chris Wray was just confirmed by the senate judiciary committee in a unanimous decision on July 20. Neil Gorsuch judiciary committee meeting was in march and wasn't approved until april. SCOTUS candidates higher level of scrutiny (no pun intended). Similar timeline but this should go faster due to position. Scheduling forecast it seems like at this point.
Senate Floor Schedule Monday, Jul 24, 2017
Nothing is more certain than nothing happening in the Trump administration.
Wray was confirmed in committee, so now it's a scheduling issue:
A full vote on Wray's confirmation is planned before the August recess. However, that recess has been pushed back further past Aug. 1.
http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/20/christopher-wray-nomination-approved-senate-judiciary-240754
Wray was voted out of committee 20-0, I don't see any obstacles to his confirmation at this point except for scheduling.
Happy Wray Day!
The average time for nomination post-Hoover was 20 days, Trump took the longest so far with 38 days.

Republicans need a win after the failure to repeal and replace/repeal Obamacare. This is a fairly easy target. McConnell already has stated he will schedule a vote before the August recess (http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/17/mcconnell-plans-wray-vote-before-recess-240650).
Wray's senate confirmation hearing commenced on July 12, 2017 https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_A._Wray

It seems like the committee hearing for Wray went well. http://www.npr.org/2017/07/12/536549751/trumps-fbi-pick-says-his-loyalty-is-to-the-constitution-and-rule-of-law He said all the right words. But looking at the chart here: http://www.npr.org/2017/07/12/536549751/trumps-fbi-pick-says-his-loyalty-is-to-the-constitution-and-rule-of-law, I think it will be very close to the July/August timeframe. With the healthcare fiasco postponed indefinitely, I think the Senate will be moving onto other business soon, so it's likely that Wray will be up for a vote soon.

After 6 months of doing nothing it is possible that they will push this out prior to taking a recess since it is a done deal other than the formality of the vote. But with the Health care fumble they are more likely to want to get out of town asap

Well. it didn't take replace long to crash and burn, and I'm pretty sure the Clean Repeal bill will go down in flames, leaving ample time for both nomination fights and starting the battle on tax reform. ACA WILL BE ALLOWED TO CRUSH ITSELF TO DEATH WITHOUT FURTHER SUPPORT OR COST SHIFTING FROM THE STATES.

http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/17/mcconnell-plans-wray-vote-before-recess-240650

Increasing odds based on same theory already stated that this is high profile, bi-partisan; creates positive narrative in light of healthcare repeal failure in the Senate prior to August recess. That they will be staying the extra two weeks anyway, confirmation of Wray creates positive momentum for other issues.. not sure about the debt limit happening however.
Im looking at this from a west wing perspective I know I have to go into recess on a positive note. Of the matters up this nomination works for that if I get nothing on healthcare or tax reform.
Pending when the floor vote is scheduled after he comes out of committee.

A good impression: FBI pick Wray deftly handled senators’ questions http://www.post-gazette.com/opinion/editorials/2017/07/17/A-good-impression-FBI-pick-Wray-deftly-handled-senators-questions/stories/201707150020

Reps need positive momentum and this nomination seems to be bipartisan which actually works. So with healthcare sidelined, nominations can be prioritized for July...especially one that's high profile bipartisan..ie. gets cable news.
This is got to be done before the health care bill now, and the Senate has a full week (July 24-31) for that after the Judiciary Committee vote.
Congress is poorly functioning. However, there seems to be unanimous support for the current nominee and the members might want to show they can achieve something.
With McConnell delaying the vote on Trumpcare until McCain returns, the confirmation vote on Wray will be on a short "to-do" list.

http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-congress-mccain-idUSKBN1A100H Yertle postpones the vote on Trumpcare until Capn John gets back from surgery, says the Senate will now take up other matters, including confirmations. They probably have the votes to get this done very quickly if they decide to.

The Judiciary committee will vote on Wray on Thursday, July 20 (https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/meetings/07/20/2017/executive-business-meeting). Given that D's have signaled they will not block him, it's likely he'll be voted out of committee. It's unclear how the delay on the health care vote may affect a floor vote for Wray, but the Senate will have 8 days in session after the committee vote to hold a floor vote, in which he's likely to gain over 51 votes.
Bumping up for the short-term on reports of bipartisan support.
http://www.politico.com/story/2017/07/13/democrats-support-quick-wray-vote-240533
Start off with a forecast 50/50
It seems that Wray will be easily confirmed by the full Senate around Aug. 1. Might be July 31 or could be Aug. 2.

Average time from nomination to confirmation is 20 days with the longest being 38. Wray was nominated June 26th. Confirmation on Aug 1 would be 35 days. There is also bipartisan support for Wray and reps have suggested his nomination will be sent to senate next week.
I see I was wrong on this. Even the Dems are signaling a quick vote next week on Wray.
As far as I can tell, there is no date set yet for the full senate to vote on Wray.

Scaling down the July chances somewhat. Wray still has to submit written answers to Senators' questions. Assuming he gets a week for that, the confirmation can realistically be scheduled from July 24 on. Also assuming it will happen before the Senate's recess, this leaves 6 working days in July and 9 in August. Given the smooth process so far, I think McConnell would like to score a victory before the Senate really gets in the thick of the heath care bill - hence the 2/1 ratio in favor of July.
The senate is busy with healthcare so probably won't get to this.

Mr. Wray appears to be well qualified as a former top Justice Dept. prosecutor. Though a few congressmen have concerns about his possible role in approving the use of torture in terror suspects (available documents were redacted), the general consensus appears to be that he is very methodical, principled, and resistant to outside influence. He publicly stated that he would voluntarily resign if forced to act unethically, even if asked by the President. The only question is the time frame.
only thing derailing him is possible impeachment hearings, which I see as very unlikely. vote is to be set for next week and he has some democrat support.
All the right answers so far

Comments: Hey, Wray..... it's YES or NO, bud. Arrgggghh!! Still, I really don't see a lot to derail his confirmation (unless he's somehow tied in to the Russians, too). Adjusting the mix. Patrick Leahy, D-Vermont, asked Wray whether Trump or anyone in his administration had asked for loyalty, to which Wray said, “My loyalty is to the Constitution.”

http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-40573675 The lad has said all the right stuff so far, which should help him move along to a fairly quick confirmation. The fact that his most recent client was the deeply sleazy Governor Christie will in the end not be held against him, but speedy confirmation will probably depend on whether Yertle the Turtle can get at least a couple of Ds to agree to vote for it. He doesn't need them for the arithmetic if the Rs hold, but the theatre--in this case, the pretense of careful deliberation--works much better with a couple of D votes.

Just saw the last ten minutes of Wray's testimony and closing remarks by a Democrat. He's in pretty easily.

As mentioned by a number of predictors, the Wray confirmation seems to be going well, with a number of both Democrats and Republican Senators indicating they are going to vote for, his FBI Director confirmation. As such, I'm revising my, prediction to 1 July - 31 July.
Wray's hearing is going well and senators (Repub and Dem) say they will vote for him. But will the vote be before Aug. 1?
Feinstein, the Ranking Dem on the Judiciary, said she'll vote for Wray, CNN reported. That significantly decreases the likelihood of Dems trying to block the confirmation.
Based on the hearing in which he did very well, it appears that he's on a fast track for confirmation.

Watching the Wray hearing, it seems to be going fairly smoothly. No major heated debates on topics, mostly policy based (except for Lindsey Graham going after Trump Jr.), very cordial (even among the Sen R's and D's).
I think tbat tbere will no repeal tbis year of ACA. That job will be held for lame duck session. Tax Reform is up next, and Wray is being laboriously taken to task in the Marble Palace.

Delay in August recess, frees up some time to confirm. Going to have to spin in opposite direction quite a bit -- still ~20 days left before deadline. http://www.rawstory.com/2017/07/us-senate-republican-leader-delays-senates-august-recess/
Russian distraction I,pedestrian action and confirmation
McConnell pushes recess out/odds incr for august

@Danbell makes a good point about political muscle which may point to increased momentum to get this and a few other things done. I believe it will be done but now, it doesn't have the deadline we want. It will be no big deal for it to go right up to the new deadline as long as it gets done. On the other hand, leaders may be thinking let's get this out of the way and not let the narrative associated with it (Comey, Russia, etc.) drag out. Although that narrative has a separate and fresh new life of its own each and every day. Waiting for signals in tomorrow's hearing.
Inverting because McConnell has pushed recess back to August.

The Sneate is notoriously slow. The committee meeting hearing Wray on the 12th, still doesn't lead me to believe that the senate can confirm before the end of the month. Possible and may be what they want. But, I before it will occur in August.
Increasing July likelihood due to postponed recess.
Altering forecast a bit. There is a lot of banter etc. about FBI confirmations and congress but there is little confidence in whether or not is able to make a decision on this before Aug 1st.
Delay in August recess, any ideas how this influences confirmation? I would say it removes some of the urgency, but not sure.

With a hearing scheduled, there is a good chance that this gets done in July. I will watch the hearing though. The Dems may like to flex a bit, and Wray has some vulnerability because of Christie connections.

Because of the sensitivities around Comey's firing and the Trump-Russia connections investigations, it sure won't be a routine confirmation.

Christopher Wray, President Trump's pick to head to the FBI, will appear before the Senate Judiciary Committee on July 12, the committee announced Wednesday. https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/onpolitics/2017/07/05/fbi-director-nominee-christopher-wray-gets-confirmation-hearing-date/453425001/

Upping July based on the Senate Hearing schedule (https://www.senate.gov/committees/committee_hearings.htm). Only one Judiciary Committee hearing this week for Wray on Wednesday. The committee has a hearing on Thursday for circuit judges that could probably be postponed to continue with Wray if needed, but McConnell is going with the spread offense, with 8 different committee hearings all beginning between 9:30 and 10:00 AM on Wednesday morning, with at least 4 of the Senate D's on those other committees.
There will be a lot of questions for Wray from senators, but he may be confirmed without too much trouble.

Apparently 65% of all Trump nominations have been filibustered, albeit for a relatively short time since nominations only require 51 votes anyway. I went through the list of the high profile nominees who were filibustered and from their first hearing to final Senate confirmation, an average of 22 days elapsed. For Christopher Wray, there are just 19 available days from July 12 to the last day of the month. Therefore, this would need to be a priority in order to beat the average time. For those higher profile nominees who weren't filibustered (Haley, Pompeo, Kelley, Mattis) the average time from their first hearing to confirmation was 9 days. The Wed. hearing will signal potential problems or not.

M. Petits-Doigts has placed the Hon. Yertle the Turtle (R-Kentucky), distinguished Senate Majority Leader, in an awkward spot. They would both like a quick win on something--anything!--to show that they occasionally have some idea of what they're doing. On the other hand, rushing to confirm the guy whose most recent gig was personal counsel to Governor Pillsbury Doughboy on the bridge deal seems unwise, no matter how stellar his career has been up to that point. Yertle will allow the Ds to dawdle and delay and declaim for a while to give the appearance of deliberation, and then there will be a vote to confirm. My personal guess (and "guess" is the operative term here) is that the hemming and hawing will meander into August while the Senate deals unsuccessfully with other matters.
There seem to be no huge objections to Wray, though his position of being Christie's defense lawyer in Bridge-gate seems unsavory. But, he did get Christie off the hook!
hearing scheduled
swapping based on recent news articles cited by people i follow. THX!

News narrative points to the possibility of Republicans negotiating with Democrats on a 'fix the markets only' healthcare bill. If McConnell makes this happen, he's working with Democrats. Then there's the issue of what gets done before the July 31 break. It could be that working with Democrats produces 2 things: the limited fix on healthcare markets and a few other things including but not limited to the Christopher Wray confirmation before they leave on vacation. One possibility is that these things get done by the end of the month and they get to leave for vacation on time. The other possibility is that they take more time showing how hard they work and don't leave till the first few days of August in order to get these things done. The third possibility is that it all falls apart and not much new gets done. I'm having difficulty assigning odds to these possibilities but leaning towards they want to leave by the end of the month.
Nudging up on news a hearing was scheduled: http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/340723-trumps-fbi-nominee-to-get-confirmation-hearing-next-week

If healthcare repeal/replace isn't coming together for Republicans, McConnell indicated that they will need to pass a smaller bill to shore up the markets that will otherwise collapse. Such a bill needs Democrats because it would be outside of the Reconciliation process, hence not filibuster proof. If McConnell decides to push such a bill through, he may not want to jam the Wray nomination and instead allow Democrats plenty of time to ask questions. On the other hand, Grassley indicated that he wanted to see Wray confirmed before the August recess making a case that McCabe has conflicts of interest. Will need to see which way it goes next Wed. In the meantime, there's a decent chance of this happening in July if the hearing goes smoothly.. upgrading July awaiting further signals from the hearing.
O had expected a floor fight to stall this then I remembered McConells Midnite hostage schrme tivht before recess hell hold them in session till he has the votes

Slight adjustment based on the Judiciary Committee announcing it will schedule Wray's hearing for next week (http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/senate/340723-trumps-fbi-nominee-to-get-confirmation-hearing-next-week). We'll see how the hearings go, but anticipate Wray to receive a lot of questions about the independence of the FBI and about Chris Christie and Bridgegate.
http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/confirmation-hearing-for-trump-fbi-director-nominee-christopher-wray-set-for-july-12/article/2627821
So Wray will be heard on July 12 in the Senate's Judiciary Committee. That leaves two full weeks for confirmation. Looks like a pretty good chance to me.
I don't think it's this likely (more like 70/30), but I'm trying to curb my score some. Can always switch back.
Too much on the Senate agenda, not enough time or political priority to schedule this confirmation vote before they return after Labor Day.
Still nothing on the schedule (https://www.senate.gov/committees/committee_hearings.htm).
Too much chaos in the Senate due to health care

There is too much going on currently on capital hill, and the White House to be able to devote the time necessary to schedule and hold confirmation hearings. Additionally, the fact that Trump does not appear to be all that enthusiastic about his nominee, means that he may not push for swift confirmation hearings. However, if the senate fails to pass its ObamaCare replacement, Trump, and senate republicans may call for an expedited confirmation hearing in order to shift attention away from their, what will be, failed bill.

Grassley may push hard for this in the coming 15 days of session, especially after asking the DOJ Inspector General to investigate Acting FBI Director McCabe (https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/2017-06-29%20CEG%20to%20DOJ%20IG%20(McCabe%20Conflicts).pdf and https://www.judiciary.senate.gov/imo/media/doc/2017-06-28%20CEG%20to%20DOJ%20(McCabe%20Continuing%20Conflicts%20Follow%20Up).pdf), but it would be surprising if McConnell allowed this to move forward unless health care completely implodes. However, the media circus around this, especially as Mueller's probe expands, runs the risk of delaying any hearings or increasing the political cost to those members of Congress who appear to act overtly partisan. And it's unclear if the WH even wants this rushed, since it doesn't help rid Trump of the Mueller investigation.
Other activities competing with discussion of nominee. Administration might prefer not to have a confirmed FBI director.
Updating for passage of time. There seems to be some political will to get him through in July, but there is lots of work to do and many potential pitfalls:
Given the current situation dealing with health care reform and the need to address tax reform, I don't believe that the Senate will confirm the FBI director before August 1, 2017
Grassley wants it done in July. The Senate CAN do 2 things at once.
Senate Judiciary Chairman Chuck Grassley (R-Iowa) recently stated he wants a confirmation vote on Wray in July. Will it happen then or is August more likely?

Updated. It's not happening tonight so before July is 0%. Wray was officially nominated 27 Jun (per @realdonaldtrump tweet) though was named three weeks ago. An apparently willing nominee is in hand. July already seems fraught, and this seems likely to be a contentious appointment. Non-controversial judges took around 50 days in the Regan era and >200 in the Obama era ( https://fas.org/sgp/crs/misc/R42732.pdf). Trump's median wait for a cabinet confirmation has been 25 days (https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/how-long-confirmations-will-take/).
Adjusting for passage of time

Healthcare is tense and in the way, Republicans want to move on to more popular topics like taxes and infrastructure, and a scattering of Wray stories have started with reference to Russia. The Russia investigation is the main way that Democrats have been able to get the attention of the media, so he's bound to pull heavy scrutiny. When Wray deleted the firm with Russian ties from his bio on june 20 -an incident with very little substance- CNN, usatoday, newsweek, and others ran stories.
Trump officially nominated Wray two days ago (http://www.cbsnews.com/news/christopher-wray-fbi-director-nomination-formally-submitted-by-white-house/).
A nominee, Christopher Wray, has been put forward. Given his political ties, healthcare being put off until after July 4, and increasing GOP unrest it may take awhile to get a vote.

I keep thinking that Donald feels he can wait on this. Let the summer go. One thing at a time. Why put another possible adversary in a post of law enforcement. I'm sure he's thinking things are running fine for now.

I am flipping my estimates for when Wray gets confirmed. While his nomination was finally formally submitted to the senate this week, they left today on a week long recess. They will be back at work on 7/7 and then go on another recess 7/28. So they will have three weeks to pass healthcare reform and raise the debt ceiling before the August recess. It's possible but unlikely I think that republicans can get Wray confirmed with everything else on their plate. Also, that before considering the other nominees awaiting senate confirmation.

I stand corrected - Wray has been formally nominated (see http://www.cbsnews.com/news/christopher-wray-fbi-director-nomination-formally-submitted-by-white-house/, thanks @stevehammons). So, although hearings have not been scheduled yet, he has a shot at being confirmed in July - if hearings are scheduled for July 10-14 (less likely given the health care bill) or even July 17-21.

Keeping up with the consensus. Also, the health care bill will take at least one week of the three Senate working weeks in July. And any delay in the official nomination beyond July 10-14 will make it impossible. The path for Wray's confirmation in July is getting rather narrow.

Congressional July 4 break is coming up, which will delay things. Wray's nomination deserves, and will probably get, extra scrutiny because of Comey's firing and the overall situation involving possible Russian intelligence penetration of the USG and U.S. society.

Apparently, the paperwork is done and now it's official. Healthcare will take up all the airtime when they get back from vacation #1. Then there are just 13 scheduled working days for the Senate in July leading to vacation #2 where they'll be gone a month. Not likely to happen unless it is a big priority which I have yet to see as there isn't a hearing scheduled yet. http://thehill.com/homenews/administration/339595-trump-sends-fbi-director-nomination-to-the-senate
Unless he gets excited about something he won't be making a move until after August for sure.

Just announced: Senate will table healthcare discussion until after July 4 recess. If true, and if they do bring up healthcare again, very unlikely that they'll be able to push out a FBI confirmation vote – especially a positive one! – before the August recess. Moving odds more towards the latter.

The delay of the health care vote until after the July 4th recess leaves 15 working days to complete a health care rewrite and vote. Wray is stills not on the Senate Judiciary Committee schedule (other nominees are).
If the health care bill is delayed for July, Senate time for Wray will be scarcer. Otherwise, he may have a decent shot.
A lot of this depends on congress' schedule, but Schumer is talking about holding up the Wray nomination: http://www.politico.com/story/2017/05/14/schumer-fbi-chief-prosecutor-238368

Following the discussion... US politics is something I do not understand... I do not get why Congress gets off not even mentioning a time table for such an important post to be filled again. Where is the public/media?
